"""
mkt-original layer — Acts chapter 7 (Stephen's speech, 59 missing verses; v55 already present)
Output: data/commentary/mkt-original/acts.json
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-acts-7-7.py

Stephen's speech is the longest speech in Acts and the most OT-saturated.
Translation decisions throughout:
- 'God of glory' (v2) renders theou tēs doxēs — genitive of quality, God as the manifesting presence
- charis (v10) rendered 'goodwill' to capture Pharaoh-court social register rather than theological 'grace'
- asteios tō theō (v20) 'no ordinary child' — a Hebraism meaning 'beautiful/fair before God'; MKT
  conventional rendering loses the divine-quality locution but opts for clarity
- logos (vv.22, 29) rendered 'speech/word' not Johannine 'Word' — context is Moses's education and flight
- lytrōtēn (v35) 'deliverer' — the unique NT use of lytrōtēs, connecting to the OT goel (kinsman-redeemer)
- logia (v38) 'living words' — the diminutive form of logos, used specifically for divine oracles
- sklērotrachēloi (v51) 'stiff-necked' — exact calque of qesheh-oref (Exod 32:9, 33:3, 5; 34:9; Deut 9:6)
- ton Dikaion (v52) 'Righteous One' — disp=4; a messianic title, not merely a moral description
- pneuma (vv.51, 55, 59) rendered 'Spirit/spirit' depending on context — the MKT distinguishes
  capitalized 'Holy Spirit' (v51, 55) from lowercase 'my spirit' (v59) following the petition structure
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new verse entries without overwriting already-present keys — safe to re-run.
    # CHANGE? If commentary JSON structure changes from {ch:{v:html}}, update this traversal.
    # VERIFY: Re-running the script should produce identical output (no duplicate or overwritten entries).
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ACTS_CH7 = {
"7": {
"1": "<p>The high priest's question 'Are these charges true?' (ei tauta houtōs echei — lit. 'if these things have it thus') is the formal forensic opening that gives Stephen the floor for his defense-speech. Rather than defending himself, he delivers a salvation-history recapitulation — the longest speech in Acts. The MKT 'Are these charges true?' accurately renders the legal formula. Stephen's 'true' will be redefined through his speech: the charge that he speaks against Moses and the temple is true in a way that vindicates rather than condemns him.</p>",
"2": "<p>'The God of glory' (ho theos tēs doxēs) is a genitive of quality: God defined by his radiant self-manifestation. The same construction appears in Ps 29:3 LXX ('the voice of the LORD is upon the waters; the God of glory thunders'). The MKT 'God of glory appeared to our father Abraham' preserves the construction. 'Father Abraham' (tō patri hēmōn Abraam) acknowledges covenant-lineage while the speech will progressively question whether ethnic descent from Abraham guarantees covenant-faithfulness. 'In Mesopotamia, before he lived in Harran' — this pre-Harran call draws on Gen 15:7 rather than Gen 11:31, locating the call in Ur.</p>",
"3": "<p>The divine command 'Leave your country and your people' quotes Gen 12:1 LXX (gē sou kai ek tēs syngenias sou) — 'your land and from your kindred.' The MKT 'go to the land I will show you' renders hēn an soi deixō accurately — the future subjunctive of divine direction: destination unknown until arrival. Stephen begins with the paradigm of obedient departure-in-faith as the characteristic form of covenant-response.</p>",
"4": "<p>'After the death of his father, God sent him (metōkisen auton) to this land' — metoikizō (to cause to migrate) is the key verb for Stephen's thesis about a God who is not confined to land or temple. God moves people; God himself moves. The MKT 'God sent him to this land where you are now living' adds the pointed 'where you are now living' (en hē hymeis nyn katoikeite) — a subtle contrast between the migrating Abraham and the land-settled accusers.</p>",
"5": "<p>'He gave him no inheritance here (klēronomian), not even enough ground to set his foot on (bēma podos)' — bēma podos echoes Deut 2:5 ('not even enough to set your foot on'). The God who promised the land to Abraham gave him none of it during his lifetime — the promise is eschatological, not immediately territorial. This is Stephen's first anti-temple-theology move: the God of Abraham is not tied to a territory because he fulfilled his promise beyond Abraham's earthly life.</p>",
"6": "<p>'God spoke to him in this way' (elalēsen de houtōs ho theos — lit. 'God spoke thus') introduces a near-quotation of Gen 15:13 LXX. 'Your descendants will be strangers in a country not their own' — paroikous (strangers, sojourners) is the key word: the patriarchs are defined as sojourners, not land-owners. The four-hundred-year figure follows the LXX of Gen 15:13 (not the 430 of Exod 12:40). The sojourner-status is the characteristic position of the covenant people.</p>",
"7": "<p>'The nation they serve as slaves' — the divine promise includes judgment on the enslaving nation and the subsequent worship at 'this place' (tō topō toutō — the same demonstrative used in the charge against Stephen, 6:13-14). Stephen's 'this place' is ambiguous: the original referent in Gen 15:14 is the promised land, not Jerusalem specifically, let alone the temple. The divine promise of worship-at-this-place predates any temple.</p>",
"8": "<p>'The covenant of circumcision' (diathēkēn peritomēs) — a genitive of content: the covenant whose sign/content is circumcision. Stephen names circumcision as the covenant-sign while the speech will conclude that the accusers are 'uncircumcised in heart' (v.51) — they have the sign without the reality. The patriarch-chain (Abraham → Isaac → Jacob → twelve patriarchs) establishes the covenant-lineage from which the Joseph story emerges.</p>",
"9": "<p>'The patriarchs were jealous (zēlōsantes) of Joseph' — zēloō carries both the positive sense (zealous for) and the negative sense (envious of); here it is clearly the negative: the brothers' jealousy drove them to sell Joseph into slavery. Stephen's speech consistently identifies the pattern of Israel rejecting God's appointed agents: they rejected Joseph, they rejected Moses (vv.27, 35, 39), they killed the prophets (v.52), and they killed Jesus. But God was with Joseph — the divine overruling of human rejection is the speech's counter-narrative.</p>",
"10": "<p>'He gave Joseph wisdom (sophia) and enabled him to gain the goodwill (charin) of Pharaoh' — charis here is rendered 'goodwill' in the MKT rather than 'grace' (disp=2: lit=grace, med=grace, tho=favor). The MKT opts for the social register of charis in a court context: the granting of favorable standing before a political superior. This is the correct contextual rendering — Gen 39:21 LXX uses the same word for Joseph finding favor in prison. The theological 'grace' sense would be an over-read here.</p>",
"11": "<p>'A famine struck all Egypt and Canaan' — the famine that drove Jacob's sons to Egypt is the providential mechanism of the Joseph story's resolution. 'Great suffering' (thlipsis megalē — great affliction) uses the same word used in Acts for the sufferings of the early church (8:1; 11:19). The ancestors' suffering in famine is the template for the community's suffering under persecution — both are moments where God's purpose is being accomplished despite (through) the tribulation.</p>",
"12": "<p>'When Jacob heard that there was grain in Egypt' — Jacob sending 'our forefathers' (tous pateras hēmōn — our fathers) to Egypt continues the communal identification: Stephen speaks as a member of the covenant people, not as an outsider. The speech is Israel's own self-critique, not a Gentile's criticism from outside. The grain-in-Egypt (sition) that Israel's ancestors sought prefigures the spiritual food available where Israel's leadership did not expect it.</p>",
"13": "<p>'On their second visit, Joseph told his brothers who he was' — the anagnōrisis (recognition) of Joseph by his brothers on the second visit is the template for the recognition of Jesus by his disciples (and eventually Israel): rejected, sold for silver, hidden, then revealed to those who had rejected him. Stephen's audience has not yet made the 'second visit' that would bring recognition. The MKT 'Joseph told his brothers who he was' renders anegnōristhē Iōsēph tois adelphois autou — 'Joseph was made known to his brothers.'</p>",
"14": "<p>'Joseph sent for his father Jacob and his whole family, seventy-five in all' — the seventy-five figure follows the LXX of Gen 46:27 (which includes Joseph's Egyptian grandsons in the count) rather than the MT's seventy. Stephen quotes the LXX throughout his speech, the Scripture of diaspora Judaism and his audience in Acts. The family-number is a minor variant between LXX and MT traditions; Stephen follows the Greek Bible he and his audience used.</p>",
"15": "<p>'Then Jacob went down to Egypt, where he and our ancestors died' — the death of Jacob and the ancestors in Egypt is stated baldly. The patriarchs died outside the promised land. Their bones were eventually brought back (v.16), but the patriarchs themselves completed their lives as sojourners (paroikoi). Stephen's accumulating point: the foundational generation of the covenant community were sojourners who died outside the land and were still recipients of the covenant promises.</p>",
"16": "<p>'Their bodies were brought back to Shechem and placed in the tomb that Abraham had bought from the sons of Hamor' — Stephen conflates two OT burial traditions (Gen 50:13 — Jacob buried at Machpelah bought from Ephron; Josh 24:32 — Joseph buried at Shechem bought from Hamor's sons). Whether this is a speech-error, a textual tradition Stephen uses, or deliberate conflation for rhetorical purposes is debated. The MKT follows the text faithfully. The burial-at-Shechem motif is significant: Shechem, not Jerusalem, is where the patriarch-bones rest.</p>",
"17": "<p>'As the time drew near for God to fulfil his promise to Abraham' (hōs de ēngizen ho chronos tēs epangelias hēs ōmologēsen ho theos tō Abraam) — the promise-fulfillment is explicitly God's initiative: 'which God had guaranteed/sworn to Abraham' (hōmologēsen — confessed/sworn solemnly). The MKT 'fulfil his promise' renders epangelia accurately. The increase of the people is not their achievement but the organic fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise.</p>",
"18": "<p>'A new king, to whom Joseph meant nothing, came to power in Egypt' — the phrase 'who did not know Joseph' (hos ouk ēdei ton Iōsēph) quotes Exod 1:8 LXX. Institutional memory fails; the political successor to the regime Joseph served has no relationship with Joseph's legacy. Stephen's point: the covenant people's security in Egypt depended on the remembrance of Joseph; when that memory is lost, persecution follows. The pattern of a new power that forgets the previous generation's servant recurs in the speech.</p>",
"19": "<p>'He dealt treacherously with our people' (katastrophisato to genos hēmōn — deceived our people by cunning) — katastrophizomai means to deal craftily with; it appears only here in the NT. The MKT 'dealt treacherously' captures the cunning-exploitation sense. The abandonment of babies (ektheta — exposed infants, a common ancient practice of infant disposal) is the ultimate threat: the covenant people's continuity is at risk from Pharaoh's decree.</p>",
"20": "<p>'Moses was born, and he was no ordinary child' (asteios tō theō — lit. 'fair/beautiful to God' or 'pleasing to God') — the Hebraism asteios tō theō is a superlative idiom. Asteios means attractive, pleasing; tō theō is a dative of reference ('to God') used as an intensifier in LXX idiom: 'a city great to God' = 'an exceedingly great city' (Jon 3:3). The MKT 'no ordinary child' chooses readability over the literal divine-quality locution. The underlying claim: Moses's birth was marked with divine favor from the outset.</p>",
"21": "<p>'Pharaoh's daughter took him and brought him up as her own son' — the adoption of Moses by Pharaoh's daughter (anethepsato — reared as her own; the same word used for the rearing of children) is the reversal of the abandonment-decree: the very dynasty that ordered infant death raises the deliverer who will bring the dynasty down. The irony is structural in Exodus and Stephen's retelling amplifies it.</p>",
"22": "<p>'Moses was educated in all the wisdom of the Egyptians and was powerful in speech and action' — logos here (dynamios en logois kai ergois — lit. 'powerful in words and works') is the functional-practical sense of speech/word, not the Johannine Logos (disp=3: lit=word, tho=the Word). The MKT 'speech and action' correctly renders this as Moses's rhetorical and practical capability — a description of complete excellence in Egyptian court culture. That Moses was 'powerful in speech' directly contradicts Exod 4:10 ('I am not eloquent'); Stephen may be describing his potential or using a different tradition.</p>",
"23": "<p>'When Moses was forty years old, he decided to visit (epeskepsasthai — to look upon with care, to visit officially) his own people, the Israelites' — episkeptomai is the word used for God's gracious visitation of his people (Luke 1:68, 78; 7:16; Acts 15:14). Moses's official-visitation of his people mirrors the divine-visitation pattern. His 'going down' to see his people echoes God's 'coming down' to see Israel's affliction (Exod 3:7-8). Moses enacts the divine compassion before he has received the divine commission.</p>",
"24": "<p>'He went to his defence (ēmynato — he defended/helped) and avenged him (epoiēsen ekdikēsin — he made/performed justice/vengeance)' — ekdikēsis is the execution of justice; it can be either righteous vindication or personal vengeance depending on context. The MKT 'avenged him by killing the Egyptian' is accurate. Stephen neither condemns nor defends the killing; he presents it as Moses's premature attempt at the deliverer-role (v.25 — he thought they would understand that God was using him).</p>",
"25": "<p>'Moses thought that his own people would realize that God was using him to rescue them' — the MKT 'God was using him to rescue them' renders synienai hoti ho theos dia cheiros autou didōsin sōtērian autois — 'would understand that God was giving salvation through his hand.' Sōtēria (salvation) is the word used for the gospel's salvation throughout Acts. Moses's first attempt at delivering Israel is an image of the rejected deliverer who is eventually vindicated — the same pattern applied to Jesus.</p>",
"26": "<p>'Moses came upon two Israelites who were fighting. He tried to reconcile them' — the verb synēllassen (he was reconciling) is imperfect: he was in the process of reconciling, attempting peace. Moses as peacemaker among his own people is the role he is appointed for; his brothers' rejection of his peacemaking mirrors Israel's rejection of the prophets and Christ. The 'Men, you are brothers; why do you want to hurt each other?' foreshadows Christ's reconciling mission and the apostolic call to peace.</p>",
"27": "<p>'Who made you ruler and judge over us?' — the rejection-question (tis se katestēsen archonta kai dikastēn — who appointed you ruler and judge?) is quoted identically in v.35 as the founding rejection that paradoxically becomes his appointment-text: the one they rejected is the one God sent. The double use of the rejection-question (vv.27 and 35) creates the chiastic structure of the Moses-narrative: rejected by man, appointed by God; rejected by Israel, vindicated by God.</p>",
"28": "<p>'Are you thinking of killing me as you killed the Egyptian yesterday?' — the irony is that the Israelite who quotes Moses's killing of the Egyptian is himself the one who will 'kill' Moses through rejection — driving him from the community. The MKT 'Are you thinking of' renders mē anelein me thēleis — 'do you not desire to kill me?' The negative particle makes this a rhetorical question expecting a negative answer, but the subtext is accusatory.</p>",
"29": "<p>'When Moses heard this, he fled to Midian, where he settled as a foreigner (paroikos — sojourner) and had two sons' — paroikos (v.29) echoes the paroikoi of v.6: the covenant people's patriarchs were sojourners, and now Moses joins their number. The word of rejection drives Moses into sojourner-status. Logos in this verse (logos de houtos — 'at this word'; disp=3 for logos) is the concrete speech-act that precipitated Moses's flight, not the Johannine Word. MKT 'when Moses heard this' accurately renders the contextual sense.</p>",
"30": "<p>'An angel appeared to Moses in the flames of a burning bush in the desert near Mount Sinai' — the theophany at Sinai (Horeb/Sinai are the same mountain) occurs after Moses's forty-year sojourn in Midian. The angel of the LORD appears in flame (en phlogi pyros — in a flame of fire) — the same pneumatological manifestation form as Pentecost (Acts 2:3). The bush burns without being consumed: an eternal, unconsumable fire that is nonetheless real and present fire.</p>",
"31": "<p>'He was amazed at the sight' (ethaumazen to horama — he was marveling at the vision) — horama is the word used in Acts for visionary experiences (Acts 9:10, 12; 10:3, 17, 19; 11:5; 12:9; 16:9, 10; 18:9). The burning bush is a horama: not an ordinary natural phenomenon but a divinely-staged vision that becomes the occasion for divine address. 'As he went over to get a closer look, he heard the Lord's voice' — the approach that brings divine address is the posture of covenant-inquiry.</p>",
"32": "<p>'I am the God of your fathers, the God of Abraham, Isaac and Jacob' — the triple patriarchal formula (ho theos tōn paterōn sou, ho theos Abraam kai Isaak kai Iakōb) quotes Exod 3:6 LXX exactly. This is the burning-bush self-identification that Jesus later uses to prove resurrection (Mark 12:26 — 'I am the God of Abraham...'; the present-tense 'I am' implies the living covenant-relationship with those still alive). 'Moses trembled with fear and did not dare to look' — entromos genomenos (having become trembling), the standard posture before the divine presence (Ezek 1:28; Dan 8:17; 10:9).</p>",
"33": "<p>'The place where you are standing is holy ground' (hē gē hēs estēkas hagia gē estin) — the holiness of the ground at the burning bush predates any constructed temple. God declares particular ground holy by his presence; the temple's holiness is derived from the divine presence, not from its construction. Stephen's anti-temple argument gathers force: the burning bush (not the Jerusalem temple) is the paradigmatic holy place — it was in the desert, outside the land.</p>",
"34": "<p>'I have indeed seen the oppression of my people in Egypt. I have heard their groaning and have come down to set them free' — the divine seeing, hearing, and descending (idōn eidon... ēkousa... katebēn — I have seen, I heard, I came down) is the triple divine engagement formula from Exod 3:7-8 LXX. The divine descent to deliver is the pattern for the Incarnation (John 1:14) and for every divine intervention. 'Now come, I will send you back to Egypt' — the sending is the pattern of the mission: God descends and then sends human agents as his representatives.</p>",
"35": "<p>'This is the same Moses they had rejected' — the threefold repetition of 'this is the same Moses' (touton ton Mōusēn — this Moses, twice in v.35, once in v.36) creates the rhetorical drumbeat of rejected-then-vindicated. 'Ruler and deliverer' (archonta kai lytrōtēn) — lytrōtēs appears only here in the NT; it is the agent noun of lytroō (to redeem/ransom), connecting to the OT goel (kinsman-redeemer). The MKT 'deliverer' captures the ransom-redemption sense. God sent him through the angel in the burning bush — the same rejected man becomes the divinely-appointed redeemer.</p>",
"36": "<p>'He led them out of Egypt and performed wonders and signs (terata kai sēmeia) in Egypt, at the Red Sea, and for forty years in the wilderness' — the wonders-and-signs formula (used in the reverse order 'signs and wonders' more commonly) anchors the Mosaic ministry. Stephen's Moses-summary (vv.35-37) is the template for the apostolic ministry: sent by God, performing signs and wonders, leading a people through a wilderness, pointing to a coming prophet. The audience can hear the parallel with Jesus.</p>",
"37": "<p>'This is the Moses who told the Israelites, God will raise up for you a prophet like me from your own people' — the quotation of Deut 18:15 ('a prophet like me') is Stephen's Christological key. Moses himself prophesied the coming of a greater prophet. Stephen's accusers who honor Moses should hear Moses's own prophecy pointing to Jesus. The rejected deliverer prophesied the coming of another rejected deliverer. The speech's implicit argument: if you rejected Jesus, you rejected Moses's own prophecy.</p>",
"38": "<p>'He was in the assembly (ekklēsia — church/assembly) in the wilderness' — the wilderness gathering is called ekklēsia, the same word used for the Christian community throughout Acts. The church in the wilderness is the OT antecedent of the NT church; the continuity is lexical and theological. 'He received living words (logia zōnta) to pass on to us' — logia is the diminutive or specialized form of logos, specifically for divine oracles (Rom 3:2; 1 Pet 4:11). The MKT 'living words' correctly renders the divine-oracle register rather than 'words' generally.</p>",
"39": "<p>'Our ancestors refused to obey him. Instead, they rejected him and in their hearts turned back to Egypt' — the heart-return to Egypt (estrapsēsan tais kardiais autōn eis Aigypton) is the inner rejection: they still thought like Egypt-slaves even after the Exodus. The pattern is applied to Stephen's audience: they have the form of covenant-faithfulness (temple, law, circumcision) but their hearts are oriented toward the security-structures of the old order. The MKT 'in their hearts turned back to Egypt' correctly captures the internal apostasy.</p>",
"40": "<p>'Make us gods who will go before us. As for this fellow Moses' — the quotation of Exod 32:1 LXX ('make us gods, elohim, who will go before us') uses plural 'gods' — the golden calf is not merely one idol but the desire for a plurality of tangible mediators. 'This fellow Moses' (ho Mōusēs houtos) uses the contemptuous demonstrative: the same distancing 'this one' used by those who reject divinely-appointed figures (John 9:29 — 'this man, we do not know where he comes from'). The MKT 'this fellow Moses who led us out of Egypt' captures the contemptuous register.</p>",
"41": "<p>'They made an idol in the form of a calf' (emoschopoisēsan — they made a calf-idol; a hapax in the NT) — the compound verb (moschon + poieō) appears to be coined for this specific act of manufacturing the golden calf. 'They revelled (euphrainthēsan) in what their own hands had made' — the joy in self-made religion is the anti-type of joy in the God-given salvation. 'The works of their hands' (ta erga tōn cheirōn autōn) is the standard OT idolatry-formula (Deut 4:28; Ps 115:4; Isa 2:8).</p>",
"42": "<p>'God turned away (estrepsen) and gave them over (paredōken) to the worship of the sun, moon and stars' — the divine abandonment formula (paredōken — he gave them over) is the same word used in Rom 1:24-28 for God's judgment on Gentile idolatry. Israel in the wilderness is subjected to the same judgment as the Gentiles: God gives them over to their chosen idols. The Amos quotation that follows ('the book of the prophets') is from Amos 5:25-27 LXX, which Stephen quotes in the next verse.</p>",
"43": "<p>'You have taken up the tabernacle of Molek and the star of your god Rephan, the idols you made to worship. Therefore I will send you into exile beyond Babylon' — Stephen's quotation of Amos 5:26-27 LXX modifies the MT's 'beyond Damascus' to 'beyond Babylon,' extending the exile's scope. Rephan is the LXX's rendering of the MT's Kiyyun (Saturn deity). The point is the continuity of idolatry: the wilderness idolatry of the golden calf eventually leads to the Assyrian-Babylonian exile. Idolatry has consequences that accumulate across generations.</p>",
"44": "<p>'Our ancestors had the tabernacle (hē skēnē — the tent) of the covenant law with them in the wilderness. It had been made as God directed Moses, according to the pattern he had seen' — the tabernacle (skēnē = tent) is God's appointed meeting place — and it is a tent, mobile, non-permanent. 'According to the pattern (typos) he had seen' quotes Exod 25:40; the heavenly pattern (typos) is the reality; the earthly tabernacle is the earthly copy. Stephen's tabernacle-theology: the earthly structure is inherently derivative and temporary.</p>",
"45": "<p>'After receiving the tabernacle, our ancestors under Joshua brought it with them when they took the land from the nations God drove out before them. It remained in the land until the time of David' — Joshua (Iēsous — the same Greek name as Jesus) brings the tabernacle (the mobile tent-presence of God) into the land. The presence of God entered the land through Joshua before any temple was built; the tent-presence preceded and survived without the stone structure for centuries.</p>",
"46": "<p>'Who enjoyed God's favour (charin para theō — grace/favor before God) and asked that he might provide a dwelling place for the God of Jacob' — David's request to build a 'dwelling' (skēnōma — a tent-dwelling) for the God of Jacob is a tent-word, not a temple-word: David's original desire was for a better tent, which God redirected. Charin para theō uses charis (disp=2) in the favor-before-God sense — David's covenantal standing before God. The MKT 'enjoyed God's favour' accurately renders the social-favor dimension.</p>",
"47": "<p>'But it was Solomon who built a house (oikon — a house) for him' — oikos (house) is the ordinary word for dwelling, here used for the temple. Stephen's formulation is pointed: the temple was Solomon's project, not David's desire, and not God's demand. The shift from skēnē (tent, God's appointed form) to oikos (permanent stone house) is a step in the wrong direction for Stephen's argument — from mobile divine presence to fixed human architecture.</p>",
"48": "<p>'However, the Most High (ho hypsistos — the exalted one) does not live in houses made by human hands (cheiropoiētois — hand-made structures)' — cheiropoiētos (made by hand) is used in the NT specifically for the contrast between human-made religion and divine reality (Mark 14:58; Eph 2:11; Heb 9:11, 24). The word carries negative connotations: idols are cheiropoiēta (Lev 26:1 LXX). Stephen's implicit argument: the Jerusalem temple, as a cheiropoiēton, belongs to the same category as the wilderness idols that Israel made with its hands.</p>",
"49": "<p>'Heaven is my throne, and the earth is my footstool. What kind of house will you build for me? says the Lord' — the Isaiah 66:1-2 quotation is the Scriptural climax of Stephen's anti-temple argument. The God who inhabits heaven and uses the entire earth as a footstool cannot be contained in a human structure. 'What kind of house will you build for me?' (poion oikon oikodométhē moi) is a rhetorical question expecting the answer: none adequate. The universe is smaller than God; no house made by human hands can contain him.</p>",
"50": "<p>'Has not my hand (hē cheir mou — my hand) made all these things?' — the divine hand that made the cosmos is contrasted with the human hands that made the temple (cheiropoiētois, v.48). God's hand made everything; human hands made a structure inside everything and claimed it could contain the Everything-maker. The Isaiah quotation ends Stephen's positive argument; what follows (v.51) is the direct accusation that functions as the speech's peroration.</p>",
"51": "<p>'You stiff-necked people! Your hearts and ears are still uncircumcised' — sklērotrachēloi (stiff-necked) is the exact LXX calque of the Hebrew qesheh-oref (Exod 32:9; 33:3, 5; 34:9; Deut 9:6, 13): the wilderness-generation's characteristic rebellion. 'Uncircumcised in hearts and ears' (apericktmētoi kardiais kai tois ōsin) quotes Lev 26:41; Deut 10:16; Jer 4:4; 6:10 — the prophetic accusation that Israel's ethnic circumcision has not produced the heart-obedience the sign points to. 'Holy Spirit' here (tō pneumati tō hagiō — the Holy Spirit; disp=3) is capitalized in the MKT correctly: the Spirit being resisted is the divine third person, not merely spiritual impetus.</p>",
"52": "<p>'Was there ever a prophet your ancestors did not persecute?' — the rhetorical question expects 'No' — the persecution of every prophet is the record. 'The Righteous One' (ton Dikaion — disp=4: lit=righteous, tho=just) is a messianic title in Acts (3:14; 22:14; cf. Isa 53:11 — 'my righteous servant'). The MKT 'Righteous One' captures the titular force: Stephen is not calling Jesus merely 'a righteous person' but using a recognized messianic designation. 'You have betrayed and murdered him' — the you-have-murdered formula applied directly to the Sanhedrin, the specific audience.</p>",
"53": "<p>'You who have received the law that was given through angels (eis diatagās angelōn — into ordinances of angels) but have not obeyed it' — the angelic mediation of the law (diatagas angelōn) is a Second Temple tradition (Gal 3:19; Heb 2:2; Deut 33:2 LXX) that elevated the law's authority by emphasizing its heavenly transmission. Stephen uses the tradition against his accusers: the very law they claim to honor came through angels; their persecution of the prophets and murder of Jesus violates the law they received through such august mediation. The law (nomos — disp=3) is 'the Law' in the MKT: Stephen treats it as a proper noun throughout.</p>",
"54": "<p>'They were furious (dieprionto tais kardiais autōn — they were sawn through in their hearts) and gnashed their teeth (ebrukon tous odontas — they gnashed/ground their teeth at him)' — dieprionto is the same verb used in Acts 5:33 for the Sanhedrin's reaction to Peter's testimony. The 'sawn through' metaphor captures inward fury that the controlled exterior barely contains. 'Gnashed their teeth' echoes Ps 35:16 and 37:12 (the wicked gnashing their teeth at the righteous); the Sanhedrin fulfills the Psalter's portrait of the wicked in their response to Stephen.</p>",
"55": "<p>Already present.</p>",
"56": "<p>'I see heaven open and the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God' — the Son of Man 'standing' (hestōta) rather than sitting is distinctive: in Dan 7:13 and Psalm 110:1 he sits at God's right hand. The standing posture suggests either active witness (standing to testify on Stephen's behalf), welcome (rising to receive the martyr), or eschatological alertness. The MKT 'Son of Man standing at the right hand of God' preserves the unusual standing-posture which the text emphasizes. Stephen's vision is the mirror of Jesus's own claim at his trial (Luke 22:69).</p>",
"57": "<p>'They covered their ears and, yelling at the top of their voices, they all rushed at him' — the ear-covering gesture (sunéschan ta ōta autōn — they held/closed their ears) is the enacted form of 'uncircumcised ears' (v.51): they literally close their ears to the testimony they do not want to hear. The 'yelling at the top of their voices' (kraxantes phōnē megalē) overwhelms Stephen's testimony with noise — the mob's sonic suppression of prophetic witness.</p>",
"58": "<p>'Dragged him out of the city and began to stone him. Meanwhile, the witnesses laid their coats at the feet of a young man named Saul' — stoning required the witnesses to cast the first stones (Deut 17:7); the garment-laying at Saul's feet implies his approving supervision (8:1 — 'Saul was consenting to his death'). Luke introduces Saul/Paul here to establish the continuity between the persecution of Stephen and the persecutor who becomes the primary witness of Acts. The witness-coats at Saul's feet are a literary promise that Saul's story is not over.</p>",
"59": "<p>'Lord Jesus, receive my spirit' (dexai to pneuma mou — receive my spirit) — Stephen's dying prayer mirrors Jesus's last words from Ps 31:5 ('Into your hand I commit my spirit,' Luke 23:46), redirected: where Jesus prays to 'Father,' Stephen prays to 'Lord Jesus.' The pneuma here (disp=3) is the human spirit — Stephen's own spirit — not the Holy Spirit. The MKT lowercase 'my spirit' correctly distinguishes this from the Holy Spirit of vv.51 and 55. Stephen dies in the posture of Jesus: committing his spirit, praying for his killers (v.60).</p>",
"60": "<p>'Lord, do not hold this sin against them' (mē stēsēs autois tautēn tēn hamartian — do not set against them this sin) — the intercessory prayer for the killers (Luke 23:34 — 'Father, forgive them') is made now to 'Lord' (Jesus). 'He fell asleep' (ekoimēthē — he fell asleep; the standard early Christian euphemism for death, using the Koine word for sleep that suggests resurrection-waking). The MKT 'fell asleep' preserves the sleep-death metaphor that the NT uses for Christian death (John 11:11-14; 1 Cor 15:18, 20, 51; 1 Thess 4:13-16). Luke's narrative of the first Christian martyr ends with the same double-forgiveness and rest that Jesus's death exhibited.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, ACTS_CH7)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'acts', existing)
    ch7_count = len(existing.get('7', {}))
    print(f'Acts 7: {ch7_count}/60 verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
